      "text": "\nIn practice I don't follow the GoF version of composite \"by the book\".  I think [[Tom Anderson]]'s comments are the most accurate.  I put \"domain\" methods into the supertype (Node interface), some of which may expose some structural information or other [[Design Burp]]s.  E.g. a method for counting the nodes exposes the fact that the object being queried might contain multiple component objects, the [[Visitor Pattern]] exposes that there are a predetermined number of subclasses that define important behaviour.  However, if possible I prefer to push methods down into the subclasses.  Methods for modifying the composite structure belong here.  Like [[Robert Di Falco]] I find that I often combine the [[Visitor Pattern]] and [[Composite Pattern]], especially if the composite structure must be modified",
